
Provider-backed external JavaScript lets builders turn non-Beanstalk files into typed package surfaces before AST.
The backend later emits runtime assets and glue only when reachable compiled code needs them.

## Main path

`src/projects/html_project/external_js/`

Related registries live under `LibrarySet`:

- `ExternalImportProviderRegistry`
- `ExternalImportProviderCache`
- `ExternalImportResolutionTable`
- `BuilderRuntimePackageMetadata`
- `ExternalPackageRegistry`

## Two emission levels

Provider-backed external JS has two emission levels:

- build-level runtime emission
- module-level glue generation

Build-level runtime emission deduplicates JS runtime assets and required runtime module specifiers across all compiled modules.
Module-level glue generation inspects external functions referenced by the emitted JS bundle and emits only the wrapper module, import preamble and import-map entries needed for that page bundle.

Don't emit glue for unused functions.
Don't emit duplicate runtime assets per page.

## Frontend surface

External import providers resolve non-Beanstalk import sources into typed package/type/function IDs before AST consumes visibility.

JavaScript export names are runtime implementation details.
Beanstalk names come from annotations.
Supported JS export forms and annotation rules belong to the language/library docs, but the compiler-design contract is simple: the frontend sees typed external package metadata, not arbitrary JavaScript source.

External packages expose opaque types, constants and free functions only.
They don't expose receiver methods.
Use source-owned wrapper types for method-style ergonomics.

## Reachability

HIR carries stable external IDs.
The JS backend records which external functions the emitted bundle references.
That metadata drives wrapper generation.

Reachability is syntactic from the selected root policy.
For HTML page bundles, use the route's entry-start reachable set.
For standalone JS, the selected policy may include every function.

## Builder-runtime packages

Builder-runtime packages such as builder-owned virtual `@web/*` packages use the same runtime asset/glue path as provider-created imports.
They are registered directly in `external_packages` and attached to module external-import metadata when reachable HIR references them.

This keeps runtime asset planning consistent across provider-created external packages, builder-runtime packages and compiler-registered external package metadata, where applicable.

## Common mistakes

- Treating external JS files as Beanstalk source modules.
- Re-reading JS annotations during backend lowering instead of using registered metadata.
- Emitting glue for every registered external function.
- Duplicating runtime assets per module or route.
- Registering external receiver methods instead of free functions plus source wrappers.
- Letting provider-backed discovery run in parallel without deterministic provider deltas and ID remapping.

